			<img id="image1" src="../media/images/lovesickremix.jpg" width="500" height="500" alt=""/>
			<img id="image2" src="../media/images/lotuseater.jpg" width="600" height="600" alt=""/>
			<img id="image3" src="../media/images/loveforthat.jpg" width="220" height="220" alt=""/>
			<img id="image4" src="../media/images/lovesick.jpg" width="600" height="600" alt=""/>
			<img id="image5" src="../media/images/muramasa.jpg" width="220" height="220" alt=""/> 
			<img id="image6" src="../media/images/nighttime.jpg" width="500" height="500" alt=""/> 
			<img id="image7" src="../media/images/1night.png" width="1000" height="905" alt=""/> 
			<img id="image8" src="../media/images/second2none.jpg" width="640" height="640" alt=""/>
			<img id="image9" src="../media/images/somedaysomewhere.jpg" width="1200" height="1200" alt=""/>
			<img id="image10" src="../media/images/soundtracktoadeath.jpg" width="1024" height="1024" alt=""/>
			<img id="image11" src="../media/images/walkingaway.jpg" width="500" height="500" alt=""/>
			<img id="image12" src="../media/images/whatifigo.jpg" width="500" height="500" alt=""/>
			</div>
			<div class="text">
				<p id="text1"> 
					"While an extended noise jam might seem like a stretch for an artist with roots in London's populist grime scene, one of Adams’ innovations as Mumdance has been to broker a truce between streetwise beats and headier textures. In fact, his upcoming mix CD for London's famed Fabric nightclub kicks off with some 15 minutes of drum-free drones, and at several points along the mix's journey to a pounding climax of piano-laced breakbeat hardcore, the momentum slows to a crawl, as though our selector has stepped in quicksand."
				</p>
				<p id="text2">  
					"Never more has that been the case than when I learned Mura Masa’s age. He’s twenty-one now, which is bad enough, but when ‘Lotus Eater’ first broke into the mainstream from Soundcloud he was just seventeen, which is disgusting. Even more galling is just how good his self-titled debut album is, though it certainly was a number of years in the making."  
				</p>
				<p id="text3">  "“Love for That” was a song, written and conducted by Mura Masa, featuring rising singer, songwriter and musician Shura. It was released in 2014 as a lead cut for Mura Masa’s debut studio album and was intended to make the album after it was declared as a non-album single. Around the time it was released, the song and it’s accompanying music video were taken down from YouTube and all music streaming platforms."
				</p>
				<p id="text4"> 
					"Whilst A$AP Rocky’s feature to the album iteration of ‘Love$ick’ adds nothing ground-breaking to the tropical steel-drum infused instrumental, it does not take too much away at the same time – the sentiment of emptiness in some specific romantic encounter remains, showing the producer’s ability (rather than the rapper’s) to imbue some more melancholy moods in the listener." 
				</p>
				<p id="text5">  
					"Mura Masa is the self-titled debut studio album by Guernsey-born music producer Alex Crossan, under his alias Mura Masa. It was released on 14 July 2017 by Polydor, Interscope, Downtown and Anchor Point Records." 
				</p>
				<p id="text6">  
					"Not sure what's the story behind this Nighttime version of Mura Masa's "What If I Go?" featuring Bonzai's beautiful vocals, but as much as I love the original - I have to say... this thing felt pretty damn good. Even somehow Christmas-y.
					All things are pretty much stripped, so the light shines on Bonzai's undoubted talents."  
				</p>
				<p id="text7"> 
					"Masa finds an ideal collaborator in Charli, whose nostalgic, lucid vocals shine through the ample space his breezy steel-drum beat and harp arpeggios provide. Masa’s simple and restrained production elevates “1 Night” above more maudlin pop fare. As of late, Charli’s been preoccupied with partying until early morning and all kinds of excess, but here she’s open and vulnerable to new love. “It was only night/But I want to go back to where we were,” she sings. Masa and Charli’s “1 Night” distills the longing and brief joy of a short lived romance over the course of a sunny, undeniably catchy few minutes." </p>
				<p id="text8"> 
					"“Second 2 None” is the fifth single off of Mura Masa’s debut self-titled album featuring the singer Christine and the Queens.The song is about the feeling of suspicion or certainty that someone’s lover is cheating on them with another. The term “second to none” is used in this case to indicate that their lover will always be first in the lives of other people that he sees and, because of that, he would leave her. However, even though this is all going on, it has happened so frequently when they were together that she has give up the hope of him coming back to her." 
				</p>
				<p id="text9"> 
					"Like a fresh spring breeze, Mura Masa’s Someday Somewhere EP is effortlessly delicate. While the songs on the new release are packed with plenty of #feels—reminiscent of those from the 18-year-old’s Soundtrack to a Death EP—this new project has him dabbling more on the pop spectrum; as heard on “Firefly”, which pairs Nao’s Alunageorge-esque vocals over a wobbly Kaytranada-inspired beat. Then “Terrible Love” gives off heavy James Blake vibes with its skeletal and staggered percussion which backs Denai Moore’s smoldering vocal work." 
				</p>
				<p id="text10"> 
					"The first track, labelled simply as the “Intro”, sets the tone with a dreamy blend of minimal synth hits and clean percussion. It’s short and sweet, but provides more than enough quality to sufficiently hook the audience. “Know Me Better” and “Money” directly follow, heralding a similar feel to the introduction. Both tracks make excellent use of chopped and pitched vocals, whilst they oppose each other with backings of birdcalls and arpeggios respectively. As a listener, you begin to immerse yourself in the narrative." 
				</p>
				<p id="text11"> 
					"Mura Masa, who has chuck an experimental spin on one of Something To Tell You’s best cuts Walking Away. Keeping the original vocal relatively intact, an array of bubblegum-like flicks and pops through a statically-scuzzy bassline and a symphonic-technologic marimba, Masa’s blissful take on the slow-burning HAIM number about heartbreak and shifts it straight into the club. Dazzling with his fresh perspective and unique electronic flair, the remix caps off a remarkable year for the young producer."
				</p>
				<p id="text12"> 
					"The song came about in a funny way,” he said. “Because the main lyric was my idea but the song ended up kind of reflecting the fact that me and Cassia [aka Bonzai] really did spend a lot of time following each other around touring that year. The song is definitely intimate to us in that way, it reminds us of that period of getting to know each other as friends. It was also the very first idea I wrote for the album, I made most of it on a train into London."
				</p>
